WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Hello, everyone. Thank you very much for having me here. I'm going to talk about wavesurfer

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:22.680
for audio notation in R. A little bit about myself. I'm currently working on my master's

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:29.639
on the theme automatic bird species recognition based on their songs. And to tackle this problem,

00:00:29.639 --> 00:00:39.080
I chose supervised machine learning, of course. And to do so, I needed label data. One can

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:44.080
split the machine learning project workflow in these three parts. Data extraction, data

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:50.000
annotation and modeling. And I think that we are pretty well served in terms of tools

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.439
in the data extraction and modeling. We have Warbler, which is an outstanding package for

00:00:55.439 --> 00:01:05.919
bioacoustics. You have all the diverse ecosystem. Keras, TensorFlow, everything. But I had a

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:14.959
really hard time labeling my data in R. Annotating. So, wavesurfer was an attempt to bridge this

00:01:14.959 --> 00:01:24.559
gap. Okay. What is I think there's a missing image here. But what is wavesurfer? It's the

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:32.080
JavaScript library for making beautiful audio visualizations for the web. And it also has

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:40.559
a rich set of plugins to work with. So, it's pretty cool and active in the community.

00:01:40.559 --> 00:01:48.400
What I did was just an HTML widget for this library, which has this pipeable API. And

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:55.680
I also implemented the plugins. The most important one which would make me choose this library was

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:02.559
the annotator or the region plugin, which allows you to draw out some areas on your

00:02:02.559 --> 00:02:09.119
audio representation and also label it. So, it's perfect for the task, right? This square,

00:02:09.119 --> 00:02:18.240
this yellow region is an example of the annotation. Another cool feature is that you can

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:24.399
visualize spectrogram instead of the sound waves, which is important for us in this task.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:31.360
One cool thing is that this representation is not available in the original JS. I tweaked it a

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:36.320
little bit in this part. It's cool, but dangerous because I'm not very skilled in the JavaScript

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:45.360
coding. But this is the API. What I would like to highlight now is the annotator app, which

00:02:46.399 --> 00:02:54.160
provides to anyone, to the researchers to start annotating their own audios right away without

00:02:54.160 --> 00:03:03.679
knowing Shiny and stuff. This requires just two inputs, the path to the wave files folder and the

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:12.880
path to where you want to store the annotations. And it is what it looks like. I'm going to zoom

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:20.960
in some key parts. Here is the main part of the app. It's where you're going to do the actual

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:29.119
notation with the point and click, resize, drag and drop and stuff. This is the widget itself.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:36.240
Here's some metadata, where is the folders and some switches like bigger spectrogram or

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:44.960
autosaving. This is the standard controllers of any media player. This table is where you can

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:54.080
navigate through your wave files and you can select the file you want to annotate and also

00:03:54.160 --> 00:04:05.039
tells whether the audio was annotated already or not. The green is the annotated audios.

00:04:06.399 --> 00:04:10.160
Here's just a feedback of what you're going to start to use it later on.

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:19.519
And this finally is what I call the region suggester. It's a cool feature that will draw

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:26.480
for you automatically regions that it thinks is the event you are looking for. So it's pretty

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:34.079
make your life easier and your job quicker. I would like to highlight the fact that you can

00:04:34.079 --> 00:04:40.640
put it on the cloud and make this laborious part of the job collaborative. So it can scale your

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:46.640
job pretty much. And this is it. Thank you very much. This is a work in progress. So

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:55.600
reach me out in GitHub and thank you very much.

